The paper proposes a method for automated facial recognition of non-human primates in the wild, which involves computer vision and machine learning techniques. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also discusses the use of deep learning and neural networks, which suggests that it could belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The proposed approach involves learning representations that are robust to nuisance factors, which could fall under cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Finally, the paper discusses the potential applications of the proposed method for wildlife conservation and conflict management, which could be relevant to cs.IR (Information Retrieval).
